### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

Sorry for opening another issue to talk about Input and signals but I had to ask about this. I saw discussions about `@Input` and `Signal` in https://github.com/angular/angular/issues/50190 and https://github.com/angular/angular/discussions/49682#:~:text=request%20for%20Angular.-,Signal%2Dbased%20inputs,-In%20signal%2Dbased but they only said about creating a new different decorator for signal inputs or create a totally different component with signal inputs which I think it's not necessary, we can just use what Angular already have and just add an extra option.

### Proposed solution

My proposal is to add one extra prop to the `@Input()` decorator options called `signal` which will tell Angular to not reassign the input but use the current signal reference to `set` the new value. See this rewrite of the RFC proposal:

```ts
@Component({
  standalone: true,
  selector: 'user-profile',
  template: `
    <p>Name: {{ firstName() }} {{ lastName() }}</p>
    <p>Account suspended: {{ suspended() }}</p>
  `,
})
export class UserProfile {
  // Create an optional input without an initial value.
  @Input({ signal: true })
  firstName = signal<string | undefined>(undefined); // Signal<string | undefined>

  // Create an input with a default value
  @Input({ signal: true })
  lastName = signal('Smith'); // Signal<string>

  // Create an input with options.
  @Input({ signal: true, alias: 'disabled' })
  suspended = signal(false); // Signal<boolean>
}
```

### Alternatives considered

The proposed solution would work just like if you had used getter and setter to set a private `Signal` value.

```ts
@Input()
get name(): string {
  return this._name();
}
set name(value: string) {
  this._name.set(value);
}
private _name = signal('');
```

Please, I ask to consider this, I've been waiting for reactive inputs so long, we already have the tools in our hands to make it possible üôè

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

router

### Description

_Context_
We are using web components to create independant micro frontends (we don't use module federation - no negociations).

All apps are Angulars and we are using hash strategy urls.

We have the root app on `mydomain.com/#/root-app` and it has sub routes on its own. Its APP_BASE_HREF is `/`.

Some routes redirect to a specific component that loads a web component from distance (load the JS bundle, inject it in head and insert in HTML the correct HTML tag to display the web component app).

So we have a child app on `mydomain.com/#/root-app/child-app`. Its APP_BASE_HREF is `/root-app/child-app`.

_The problem_
I go on the child-app route `mydomain.com/#/root-app/child-app`, it properly loads the child-app, I can navigate in it, no problems. If I'm navigating through Angular's router no problems, I can go in my root-app, the child-app's router does not react.

But, when I'm in my child-app, if I'm modifying the browser url to point to another route of my root-app, the child-app's router is triggered, and cause errors (redirection to a custom made 404 page, and/or errors in console logs).

I've found nothing in Angular 15 code that filters popState.

### Proposed solution

I'm wondering if Angular should do the filtering (like done in my alternative solution), or provide a clean way to active/define it.

### Alternatives considered

So in my child-app, I came up with this solution, to filter the `LocationStrategy.onPopState` before sending the event to the router.

```typescript
// there are  // @ts-ignore because I'm accessing private properties
@Injectable()
export class CustomHashLocationStrategy extends HashLocationStrategy {

    constructor(
        platformLocation: PlatformLocation,
        @Optional() @Inject(APP_BASE_HREF) baseHref?: string) {
        super(platformLocation, baseHref);
    }

    override onPopState(fn: LocationChangeListener): void {
        const filteredFn = (event: any) => {
            // we only execute the callback if the browser url contains the this._baseHref
            // @ts-ignore
            if (location.hash.indexOf(this._baseHref) !== -1) {
                fn(event);
            }
        };
        super.onPopState(filteredFn);
    }
}

NgModule({
    ...
    providers: [
        {provide: APP_BASE_HREF, useValue: environment.baseUrl},
        {provide: LocationStrategy, useClass: CustomHashLocationStrategy},
        ...
    ]
})

```

